About
Experience the world's largest maritime museum, filled with inspirational stories of exploration and endeavour at sea and packed to the gunwales with intriguing objects and fascinating galleries. See the uniform Nelson wore at the Battle of Trafalgar, steer a ship into port and fire at pesky pirates.
Duration: 2-3 hours

The area

Address
Neighborhood: Greenwich
Greenwich Mean Time starts here, so to speak, as the very concept of global time was established at Royal Observatory, just one of several buildings of architectural interest in Greenwich. Indeed, the whole of Greenwich's historic town center, its Royal Park and a number of related buildings (and one world famous ship, the Cutty Sark) make up the UNESCO World Heritage site known as Maritime Greenwich. Today a laser beam is shot out across the night sky from the Observatory to mark the location of the Prime Meridian. Other bold (some say brash) 21st century additions to the area include landmarks such as The O2 entertainment complex (previously known as the Millennium Dome) and the Air Line cable cars, which offer scenic transport across the Thames between North Greenwich and the Royal Docks.

    Nice museum for nautical history and entertainment
    A nice free museum when visiting Greenwich. A love of nautical adventure and history is essential to benefit from the museum. The staff are very friendly and helpful to visitors. The museum is not too large and clearly laid out. There are various play areas for children. There is a cafe and plenty of seats available to take a break. It has a family-friendly feel and takes around an hour to visit at a quick pace. There are some good historical sections, for those wishing to learn more about maritime history. It is good for a quick visit and helpful to keep the little ones entertained for a while.
